items.name: Koroks - Legend of Zelda Series
items.description:
Koroks, you know the little gusy in Zelda games that you find or wear large backpacks, or you help water seeds on islands to spread the great forest.

Anyway, by request of my niece who wanted korok coloring pages made by me I made this lora.

I trained it with done by hand labelling, so I gave nicknames to the different leaf style faces, a few styles of the art I put into it and things like that I'll try to list all of it here.

a typical prompt for this would look like: "korok, standing, green heart shaped leaf face, brown striped body, forest background, cell shaded style", so [trigger], [action], [face style], [body style], [background], [art style]

another special example would be Hestu which looks something like: "korok, standing, named hestu, large, leaf as beard, leaves as hair, green striped body, holding maracas, wearing a satchel, mountain region background, cell shaded style"

Actions trained:

standing

too big backpack

running

the main leaf faces are:

the main styles are:

cell shaded style looks like Breath of the wild or Tears of the kingdom, rough illustration was trained on the concept art from wind waker (though it didn't come out as good as I wanted). Metal vector style was from some metal pins I liked the look of, the rest are self explanitory.

Anyway enjoy

items.name: Andre Derain Style
items.description:
André Derain was a French painter and co-founder of the Fauvism movement in the early 20th century.

His style can be described as bold, vibrant, and characterized by the use of intense and non-naturalistic colors. Derain's paintings often featured landscapes, portraits, and still lifes, which he approached with a sense of freedom and experimentation.

Derain was known for his ability to capture the essence of a subject through simplified forms and expressive brushwork. He emphasized the emotional impact of color, using bold, arbitrary hues to create a heightened sense of energy and visual impact.

His work demonstrated a departure from traditional academic approaches and a rejection of naturalistic representation. Derain embraced the use of vivid, non-naturalistic colors to convey a sense of heightened emotion and expression.

During his career, Derain explored various styles and techniques, including a period of influence from African art and a return to more classical themes in his later works.

André Derain's contributions to the Fauvist movement, with his emphasis on vibrant color and expressive brushwork, played a significant role in the development of modern art. His bold and innovative approach continues to inspire and influence artists to this day.

items.name: Andrew Atroshenko Style
items.description:
Andrew Atroshenko is a contemporary Russian artist known for his romantic and emotive paintings.

His style can be described as figurative, expressive, and imbued with a sense of drama. Atroshenko's artwork often features elegant figures, usually women, in intimate settings or engaged in introspective moments.

He employs a distinctive technique that combines loose brushwork with rich textures, creating a dynamic and textured surface that adds depth and dimension to his paintings. Atroshenko's use of vibrant colors, particularly in his depiction of clothing and backgrounds, enhances the visual impact of his compositions.

His paintings evoke a strong emotional response, often capturing a sense of longing, nostalgia, or romantic contemplation. Atroshenko's attention to detail and ability to convey subtle gestures and expressions brings his figures to life, allowing viewers to connect with their emotions and narratives.

Andrew Atroshenko's art is widely collected and exhibited internationally. His evocative and expressive paintings continue to resonate with audiences, inviting them into a world of romance, beauty, and introspection.

items.name: Anna Maria Garthwaite Style
items.description:
Anna Maria Garthwaite was an English textile designer and silk weaver known for her significant contributions to the silk industry in the 18th century.

Garthwaite's designs were highly sought after during her time and are still admired today. She was particularly known for her intricate floral patterns and botanical motifs, which showcased her exceptional skill in creating detailed and naturalistic designs.

Her designs often featured a wide variety of flowers, foliage, and other organic elements, which were meticulously woven into silk fabrics using a drawloom—a complex weaving device that allowed for intricate patterns.

Garthwaite's designs were characterized by their elegance, delicacy, and attention to detail. Her work showcased a refined sense of composition and color, incorporating a harmonious blend of hues and shades.

She drew inspiration from nature, botanical illustrations, and the gardens of the Georgian era. Garthwaite's patterns graced the wardrobes of fashionable individuals, including royalty and the aristocracy.

Anna Maria Garthwaite's contributions to the silk industry and her skill as a textile designer played a significant role in the development of the silk weaving tradition in 18th-century England. Her designs continue to be appreciated for their beauty, craftsmanship, and their representation of the artistic legacy of the era.

items.name: Goldie - Hentai University
items.description:
This is a LoRA for the character Goldie, from Hentai University a game by Noodle Jacuzzi.

If you want to give me a tip for these, it would be greatly appreciated. I recently had a pipe burst in my house, and that is... Expensive, especially when compounded with the fact that it's taken about a month to fix. If it even gets fixed when it's supposed to this week and some other problem doesn't come up.

I have a Ko-Fi here, and any tip genuinely helps a lot for making that plumbing nightmare a bit less of a problem.

Now, on to the more fun part -

Goldie's art is from the artist Uo Denim, the set -

Boku no Hajimete wa Bitch Gal

I've been working my way through making these for all the characters currently in the game, and sharing them in the Discord for HU, but figured I should also put them up here.

In general, I'm working from pretty limited image sets, so expect the results to be a bit wonky at times.

I recommend a weight of around 0.5, possibly lower depending if you're combining the character LoRA with other styles/costumes/etc. along with tagging some defining characteristics of the character you're generating. Higher than that can really push the artist's original style, and may cause you issues.

All characters I train have a "character tag" added into the set to help generate them fairly reliably.

Recommended LoRA Weight - 0.5 for fairly flexible, higher if you want more of the original artist's style, lower if it doesn't play nice with other loras.

Character tag - HUGoldie
Recommended tags - blonde hair, long hair, blue eyes, dark skin, large breasts,

You may want to up the emphasis on dark skin, depending on the lora you combine it with. You know how AI generations go pushing pale girls.

I may have forgotten to check and tag eye color when doing my testing, but hey. If you want it to be "set accurate" be sure to tag.

I've got quite a backlog of these made up already, so I'll be uploading them on and off.

Check my other uploads as I put them out for more HU characters, and if you want any specific character put up soon, let me know.
